div.p:
2. The Second Requiſite to conſtitute a Fluid Body, is, That it ſhould have conſiderable Vacuities or Pores, betwixt the Parts of it;
                           Porouſneſs in Bodies requiſite to their Fluidity.
                         for if there were no ſuch Spaces, the Parts being put into Motion, would not have Space to continue it in, nor could one Particle by the Impulſe of another, be forc'd to give way. But before I proceed, it will be requiſite here to Note, That by Spaces, I would not be thought to mean Vacuities properly ſo call'd; but that there is no ſuch Subſtance betwixt them, which will obſtruct the Motions of the more Solid Parts.

